## Gate 3 — Authentication & Authorization

Implement the auth strategy specified in the brief:

**For email + password:**
- Password hashing: bcrypt (min cost 12) or argon2
- JWT: access token (15 min expiry) + refresh token (7 day, httpOnly cookie)
- Endpoints: `POST /api/auth/register`, `POST /api/auth/login`, `POST /api/auth/refresh`, `POST /api/auth/logout`
- Rate limiting on login: max 5 attempts per 15 min per IP

**For OAuth:**
- Use a proven library (Passport.js, next-auth, etc.) — do not hand-roll OAuth flows
- Store provider ID and email; do not store third-party tokens longer than needed

**For all strategies:**
- Middleware/guard that attaches the authenticated user to the request context
- Role/permission model if the spec requires it (document roles in `docs/be-handoff.md`)
- All protected routes return `401` for unauthenticated, `403` for unauthorised requests

**Output block:**
```
GATE 3 STATUS: APPROVED | REVISION NEEDED
Auth strategy: [strategy]
Protected routes: [count]
```

---

## Gate 4 — API Endpoints

Implement every endpoint listed in `docs/fe-handoff.md` plus any additional ones identified in Gate 1.

For each endpoint:

```
POST /api/auth/login
Request:  { email: string, password: string }
Response: 200 { token: string, user: UserDTO }
          400 { error: "validation_error", fields: {...} }
          401 { error: "invalid_credentials" }
Auth:     public
```

Implementation requirements:
- Input validation on every request body and query param (use a schema validator: Zod, Yup, Joi, Pydantic, etc.)
- Consistent error response shape: `{ error: string, fields?: Record<string, string> }`
- HTTP status codes used semantically (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 409, 422, 500)
- Pagination for any list endpoint: `?page=1&limit=20`, response includes `{ data: [], total: number, page: number, limit: number }`
- No business logic in route handlers — extract to service layer
- No raw SQL in route handlers — use ORM or query builder

**Output block:**
```
GATE 4 STATUS: APPROVED | REVISION NEEDED
Endpoints implemented: [count / list]
```

---

## Gate 5 — Data Layer & Business Logic

Implement the service layer:

- One service file per entity/domain (e.g. `UserService`, `OrderService`)
- Services receive validated data from the controller and return typed results
- Error types are explicit — services throw typed errors, not generic `Error`
- Database transactions used wherever multiple writes must be atomic
- No N+1 queries — use joins, eager loading, or `SELECT IN` for related data

**Output block:**
```
GATE 5 STATUS: APPROVED | REVISION NEEDED
```

---

## Gate 6 — Integrations & Messaging

For each third-party service or messaging queue in the brief:

**Email (transactional):**
- Use a provider SDK (Resend, SendGrid, Postmark, etc.)
- Templates stored as files, not inline strings
- All sends go through a single `EmailService` — never call the provider directly from a route

**Background jobs / queues (if required):**
- Define job types with typed payloads
- Workers are separate processes — not inline in API handlers
- Failed jobs log to a dead-letter queue or table with the error and payload
- Document job types in `docs/be-handoff.md`

**Third-party APIs:**
- Each integration gets its own client module: `src/lib/[service]-client.ts`
- Credentials read from environment variables only
- Retries with exponential backoff for transient failures
- Errors wrapped in domain-specific errors (do not surface raw provider errors to the API consumer)

If the brief specified no integrations, skip and note "No integrations required."

**Output block:**
```
GATE 6 STATUS: APPROVED | REVISION NEEDED
Integrations implemented: [list or "none"]
```

---

## Gate 7 — Security Hardening

Before handoff, run a security self-audit:

- [ ] No secrets in code — all credentials in `.env`, `.env.example` has placeholder values
- [ ] CORS configured: allow only the frontend origin(s), not `*` in production
- [ ] Helmet / security headers applied
- [ ] Rate limiting on auth and any write endpoints
- [ ] File uploads (if any): validate MIME type server-side, store in object storage (not local disk in production), max file size enforced
- [ ] SQL injection: impossible if ORM/parameterised queries used — confirm this
- [ ] Mass assignment: only explicitly whitelisted fields are updated from request body
- [ ] Sensitive fields (`password`, `token`) never returned in API responses
- [ ] All environment variables documented in `.env.example`

Fix all failures before proceeding.

**Output block:**
```
GATE 7 STATUS: APPROVED | REVISION NEEDED
Security issues fixed: [list]
```

